<dl id="n12074a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12074a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12074a"> 74(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ for plunder&apos; sake ~ <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n12074a"><li>FW 81.31 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n12074a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n12074a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n12074a">MS BL 47472-158</ms> </li><li>JJA 46:034 <a name="d1A3d" href="../../ff/fdra/dda.htm#d1A3d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/d1A3d.htm#n12074a">Draft: I.4&sect;1A.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">By the divine providence of God, it so happened, that in <mark>his tender years</mark> he should be led to that nation <font color="green">[Ireland]</font>, so that in his youth he should learn the language of the people, whose apostle he was afterwards destined to become. At that period Irish fleets were accustomed to sail over to Britain <mark>for the sake of plunder</mark>, and to bring back to Ireland whomsoever they made prisoners. It chanced, therefore, that the venerated youth, with his sister, named Lupita, should be taken captives amongst others. <small> William Canon Fleming, <a name="WFBS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WFBS"><cite title="source">Boulogne-sur-mer: St Patrick's native town</cite></a> (1907) 62</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Play on &lsquo;for God&apos;s sake&rsquo;. </mm> </dd></dl>
